# Docker & Kubernetes Standards

## Dockerfile
- Use multi-stage builds: builder → runner
- Pin base image versions: `node:20.11-alpine3.19`, not `node:latest`
- Run as non-root user
- Use `.dockerignore` to exclude node_modules, .git, .env files
- Order layers for optimal caching: dependencies before source code

<example>
# ✅ Correct: multi-stage, pinned version, non-root
FROM node:20.11-alpine3.19 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm ci --production=false
COPY . .
RUN npm run build

FROM node:20.11-alpine3.19 AS runner
RUN addgroup -g 1001 -S appgroup && adduser -S appuser -u 1001
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app/dist ./dist
COPY --from=builder /app/node_modules ./node_modules
USER appuser
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "dist/main.js"]
</example>

## Kubernetes
- Use resource limits on all containers
- Define liveness and readiness probes
- Use ConfigMaps for non-sensitive config, Secrets for sensitive data
- Namespace per environment: `dev`, `staging`, `production`

## Terraform
- Use modules for reusable infrastructure
- State stored remotely (Azure Storage Account / S3)
- Tag all resources with `environment`, `team`, `service`
- Plan before apply — never `terraform apply` without reviewing plan
